**Shopify Financial Services Inc.**  
**Business Plan**

1. # Introduction

   

Shopify Financial Services Inc. (“Shopify FS”) is a Delaware corporation that was formed on December 18, 2024\. Shopify FS was formed for the purpose of obtaining all state licenses and federal registrations required for it to engage in the proposed activities described in Section III below. 

Shopify FS is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Shopify Holdings (USA) 2 Inc. (“Shopify USA”), a Delaware corporation. Shopify USA is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Shopify Inc. (“Shopify”), a publicly traded Canadian corporation (NASDAQ: “SHOP”).

2. # Current Activities of Affiliates

   

Shopify is a leading e-commerce platform that empowers individuals and businesses to create and manage their online and retail stores. Since its launch in 2006, Shopify has rapidly grown, now supporting millions of merchants (each, a “Merchant*”)* globally, and over 10% of all commerce in the United States. In addition, Shopify’s consumer-facing e-commerce platform (the “Shop App” (available at [https://shop.app](https://shop.app))) enables shoppers (each, a “Shopper”) to browse and purchase from various Merchants, track orders, and get personalized product recommendations. Additionally, Shop App enables Shoppers to manage past purchases, fostering a better relationship between Merchants and Shoppers and enhancing brand loyalty. Recognizing that its mission to make commerce better for everyone required a focus not only on Merchants but also on Shoppers, Shopify developed a pioneering pass-through digital wallet (“Shop Pay”) that allows Shoppers to make quick and easy online purchases. 

Shop Pay is currently used by over 150 million Shoppers globally and is the gold standard for trusted commerce across the internet. Shop Pay does not presently store any value, but rather merely saves Shoppers’ shipping and payment information (e.g., debit and credit card information) thereby enabling faster checkouts across Merchants. Shoppers are more likely to make a purchase when they can use their Shop Pay account, in part due to the ease of use their saved preferences provide. Shoppers also rely on Shop Pay because of its robust security measures built to safeguard Shoppers’ information. Finally, Shop Pay features a promotional rewards program that allows Shoppers to earn rewards for their purchases (the “Rewards Program”) and permits Shoppers to redeem rewards for discounts on future transactions. 

Shopify FS shares Shopify’s mission of improving commerce for everyone, and was created to offer a stored value digital wallet as an additional payment method within Shop Pay (the “Shop Pay Wallet Balance”).

3. # Overview of Proposed Activities

   1. ## Shop Pay Wallet Balance

   

Shopify FS intends to make the Shop Pay Wallet Balance available to residents of the 50 U.S. states and the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico via the Shop App and Shop Pay checkouts once it has obtained the licenses and authorizations necessary to do so[^1]. Shopify FS will only provide its regulated services to Shoppers who open a Shop Pay Wallet Balance account via the Shop App or Shop Pay checkouts.

The Shop Pay Wallet Balance will enable Shoppers to store funds for future purchases. Shoppers will have the opportunity to fund their Shop Pay Wallet Balances by transferring money directly from their bank accounts via ACH. 

As the issuer of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance, Shopify FS will hold all funds it receives in connection with the Shop Pay Wallet Balance in one or more segregated omnibus deposit accounts at one or more federally insured financial institutions (each such financial institution, a “Bank Partner”) titled in Shopify FS’ name and held for the benefit of Shoppers (each such account, a “FBO Account”). Upon a Shopper’s withdrawal or transfer from their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, Shopify FS will withdraw a corresponding amount of funds from the FBO Account and remit such funds to the Shopper or a Merchant in accordance with the Shopper’s instructions. 

Shoppers may only withdraw funds to their own external bank accounts or use funds in the Shop Pay Wallet Balance to pay Merchants. Shoppers cannot use their Shop Pay Wallet Balances to fund P2P transactions or transactions with merchants that are not Shopify Merchants.

When making a payment using the Shop Pay Wallet Balance, Shoppers will be able to split their payments to Merchants across the Shop Pay Wallet Balance and an additional payment type to cover any difference in the value in their Shop Pay Wallet Balance and their cart totals (such payment, a “Split Payment”). Refunds will be allocated to the original form of payment.[^2] 

Diagrams depicting the anticipated flow of funds for a typical Shop Pay Wallet Balance transaction are included in the Flow of Funds Structure in Attachment A.

2. ## Marketing Strategy, Target Markets, and Competition

Marketing Strategy. Shopify (on behalf of Shopify FS) anticipates deploying a strategic approach to marketing the Shop Pay Wallet Balance. In all cases, however, Shopify FS will be clearly identified as the provider of regulated services. 

With a goal of driving awareness and discovery of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance for both current and potential customers of Shopify, Shopify plans to emphasize educational initiatives, retention strategies such as rewards through the Rewards Program, and the security and ease of use of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance. Shopify further plans to host a virtual product launch event to introduce the Shop Pay Wallet Balance to influential tech journalists, bloggers, and Shopify power users. In addition, Shopify will use marketing tools such as search engine optimization techniques, pay-per-click campaigns, social media and email advertisements, detailed product demos, user testimonials, live question and answer sessions, blog posts and articles, and whitepapers and case studies to increase awareness and understanding of the benefits of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance for Merchants and Shoppers. Shopify intends to offer promotional discounts on transaction fees in the Shop App for Merchants on transactions that use the Shop Pay Wallet Balance and will offer special rewards to Shoppers through the Rewards Program for early adopters of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance. Finally, Shopify plans to implement a feedback system to collect insights for continuous product improvement from early adopters and to tweak the marketing strategies based on analytics and feedback.

Target Markets. Shopify FS’ target market for the Shop Pay Wallet Balance includes both existing Shop Pay users and new potential users of Shop Pay and the Shop Pay Wallet Balance. As described above, Shopify FS intends to appeal to potential Shop Pay Wallet Balance users by highlighting the unique benefits and simplicity of the Shop Pay Wallet Balance.

Competition. Shopify FS believes its products will better meet consumer needs than alternatives currently available in the market (including non-digital financial services and those services offered by traditional financial institutions). In particular, the intersection of how Shoppers will discover brands on the Shop App, build loyalty through rewards, and have their Shop Pay Wallet Balance available to them in checkouts powered by Shop Pay puts Shopify FS in a position to deliver a compelling offering to consumers. Shopify FS has the technology and talent to build an easy-to-use digital interface, robust security features, convenient loading of funds, versatile rewards, and reduced friction via contactless payment processing online. As a result, Shopify FS believes that the Shop Pay Wallet Balance will be an attractive offering compared to other digital wallet alternatives.

4. # Fee Schedule

Shopify FS intends to offer the Shop Pay Wallet Balance to Shoppers free of charge and will generate income from interest income on funds it holds for Shoppers in the FBO Account. Shopify will reimburse Shopify FS for its costs, plus a profit element pursuant to one or more intercompany agreements as described below. Shopify generates revenue through a multifaceted business model that is intricately tied to the success of Merchants. By providing a comprehensive platform equipped with tools that empower Merchants to drive sales, Shopify not only enhances Merchant success but simultaneously increases its own revenue streams. The more Merchants grow, the more opportunities Shopify has to generate revenue from subscriptions, transaction fees, additional services, and premium offerings. This symbiotic relationship is at the core of Shopify's business model, making Shopify a powerful partner for entrepreneurs worldwide.

5. # Capitalization

Shopify will support the ongoing capital requirements of Shopify FS, and will provide capital infusions into Shopify FS as needed in order for Shopify FS to maintain its minimum net worth requirements.

6. # Compliance

   

	Shopify FS will implement robust policies and operational plans to manage risk and meet regulatory obligations. This includes the following: (i) AML/KYC protocols: comprehensive identity verification processes, transaction monitoring, and reporting systems; (ii) fraud prevention: advanced algorithms to detect and prevent fraudulent activity in real-time; and (iii) regulatory compliance: adherence to all regulatory requirements, including the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws.

7. # Operating Structure

As noted above, Shopify FS is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Shopify USA, which is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Shopify. Shopify FS and Shopify have entered into an Intercompany Services Agreement, pursuant to which Shopify FS will provide certain services to Shopify, in exchange for compensation, and Shopify will also have specified responsibilities in connection with Shopify FS’ services. Shopify’s responsibilities with respect to Shopify FS’ services will include:

* Administrative Services and Support: Shopify will provide administrative services to Shopify FS, including mail, facilities, benefits administration, human resources administration, and related support.  
* Accounting and Treasury Services and Support: Shopify will provide accounting and treasury services to Shopify FS, including general accounting, accounts payable, invoicing, tax, and treasury services, and related support.  
* Technical Services and Support: Shopify will provide technical services and support to Shopify FS, including telecommunication services, hardware and software maintenance and distribution, network services, data warehousing, platform integration, and related support.  
* Fraud and Risk Monitoring Services and Support: Shopify will provide access to, and maintain, its fraud and risk monitoring systems and related infrastructure established to support the services provided by Shopify FS, including but not limited to cybersecurity.  
* Cybersecurity Services and Support: Shopify will provide support to Shopify FS in maintaining a cybersecurity program that protects the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of Shopify FS’ information systems.

Shopify FS relies on shared employees with Shopify, who provide support to Shopify FS pursuant to the Intercompany Services Agreement described above. Shopify currently employs approximately 8,100 full-time employees. Once operational, Shopify FS will make dedicated employee hires as necessary to support its business volume.

8. # Authorized Agents

Shopify FS does not have any current plans to establish any authorized agent relationships or otherwise use authorized agents in conducting its proposed money transmission activities.

# Attachment A

**Flow of Funds Structure**[^3]  
![][image1]

1. **Shop Pay Wallet Balance – ACH Funding and Withdrawal** 

**![][image2]**  
**Funds Flow: Depositing funds to balance**

**![][image3]**  
**Funds Flow: Withdrawing funds from balance**

1. **A Shopper initiates an ACH Transaction through the Shop App or in a Shop Pay checkout on Web**  
     
   A Shopper initiates an “ACH Transaction” from their Shop Pay Wallet Balance through the Shop App or in a Shop Pay checkout. In an ACH Transaction, the Shopper may either be (i) funding their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, or (ii) withdrawing funds to transfer them out of their Shop Pay Wallet Balance to the Shopper’s linked external bank account. When a Shopper initiates an ACH Transaction to fund their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, a corresponding money transmission liability is created for Shopify FS.

2. **Shopify FS confirms receipt of funds from the Shopper / initiates withdrawal process**   
     
   1. If the Shopper is funding their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, the Bank Partner acts as the Originating Depository Financial Institution (“ODFI”) and initiates an ACH debit to the Shopper’s external bank account at a Receiving Depository Financial Institution (“RDFI”) to transfer the Shopper’s funds to the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance—*i.e.*, the Shopper’s balance within the FBO Account. The Shopper-facing user interface clearly communicates that the funds are "in transit" and may take up to three(3) business days to become available for use.   
        
   2. If the Shopper is withdrawing funds from the Shop Pay Wallet Balance, the Bank Partner acts as the ODFI and initiates an ACH credit to the Shopper’s RDFI to transfer funds from the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance—*i.e.*, from the Shopper’s balance in the FBO Account—to the Shopper’s external bank account. Shopify FS’ money transmission liability is extinguished once the funds have settled to the Shopper’s external bank account, which typically occurs within three (3) business days, as described below. 

   

   Upon deposit or withdrawal of funds, transaction details are sent from the Bank Partner to Shopify FS. Shopify FS validates key information and compares it to the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance account information. Bank Partner facilitates the actual movement of funds between the ODFI and RDFI, i.e., the settlement process. 

   

3. **Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance is updated**  
     
   The Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance is debited or credited based on the outcome of the transaction.  
     
   1. If the Shopper is depositing funds to their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, the Shopper’s external bank account is debited for the transaction amount as described above. A credit will be reflected in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance for the transaction amount upon settlement of such funds into the FBO Account. 

   

   2. If the Shopper is withdrawing funds from their Shop Pay Wallet Balance, the FBO Account is charged for the transaction amount as described above. A debit will be reflected in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance for the transaction amount upon settlement of such funds into the Shopper’s external bank account. 

   

4. **Shopify FS ensures ledger accuracy of the deposit**  
     
   1. For deposits, Shopify FS compares the increase in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance with the increase attributed to the Shopper’s deposit in the FBO Account to ensure they are equal.

   2. If a Shopper is making a withdrawal, Shopify FS compares the decrease in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance with the decrease attributed to the Shopper’s withdrawal from the FBO Account to ensure they are equal.

2. **Shopper Makes a Purchase | US Shopper | Merchant Anywhere | Stored Value Only**

**![][image4]**  
**Funds Flow: Purchase with stored value**

1. **Shopper initiates stored value purchase process via a Merchant checkout on the Shop App or in a Shop Pay checkout on Web**  
     
   Shopify FS is notified that a Shopper has checked out from a purchase from a Merchant and selected Shop Pay Wallet Balance as the payment method.  
     
2. **Shopify FS confirms availability of funds**  
     
   Shopify FS assesses the Shopper’s internal ledger balances daily. At the time of checkout, Shopify FS confirms whether the Shopper has sufficient funds available for the chosen Merchant purchase. If sufficient funds are available, Shopify FS will instruct Shopify via API to approve the checkout request. If sufficient funds are unavailable, Shopify FS instructs Shopify via API to reject the checkout request. 

3. **Shopify FS instructs the Bank Partner to transfer funds to the Payment Partner**  
     
   Daily at a minimum, or more frequently, Shopify FS instructs the Bank Partner to send Shop Pay Wallet Balance transaction amounts to Stripe, Inc., PayPal, Inc. or another similar financial partner (each a “Payment Partner”). The Payment Partner will be responsible for exchanging any payments processed into the Merchant’s preferred payout currency. The Merchant will be responsible to the Payment Partner for any payment processing and/or currency conversion related fees.  
     
   These amounts represent batched Shopper purchases that have been previously approved. Shopify FS payments to Payment Partner may be made in one or many ACH payments, depending on transaction volume. The Bank Partner acts as the ODFI and the Payment Partner’s bank partner acts as the RDFI. 

4. **Bank Partner facilitates the actual movement of funds between Shopify FS (ODFI) and Payment Partner (RDFI)**  
     
   Daily at a minimum, or more frequently, Bank Partner acts on Shopify FS’ instructions to send Shop Pay Wallet Balance transaction amounts to the Payment Partner. In certain circumstances Shopify FS and the Payment Partner may decide to net Shoppers’ payments and refunds against one another. Any amounts flowing between Shopify FS and the Payment Partner will be reconciled and agreed to by both parties.   
     
5. **The Payment Partner receives funds into the merchant’s account**  
     
   The Merchant receives the funds into the Merchant’s account at the Payment Partner, with funds typically settling within two (2) business days from the day that the transfer is initiated. Shopify FS’ money transmission liability is extinguished, and a corresponding debit is reflected in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance. 

6. **Shopify FS reconciles ledger and bank transaction associated with the purchase**  
     
   Shopify FS compares the decrease in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance with the decrease attributed to the Shopper’s purchase to ensure they are equal. This is completed at both the individual transaction and aggregate FBO account levels.

3. **Shopper Makes a Purchase – Split Payment**

**![][image5]**  
**Funds Flow: Purchase with split payment**

1. **Shopper initiates Split Payment purchase process via a Merchant checkout on the Shop App or in a Shop Pay checkout on Web**  
     
   Shopify FS is notified that a Shopper has made a purchase from a Merchant using a Split Payment, which combines funds from the Shopper's Shop Pay Wallet Balance and another Merchant-accepted payment method, such as a credit card or debit card (each a “Payment Card”).  
     
2. **Shopify FS confirms availability of funds**  
     
   Shopify FS assesses the Shopper’s internal ledger balances daily. At the time of checkout, Shopify FS confirms whether the Shopper has funds available in its Shop Pay Wallet Balance. If sufficient funds are available, Shopify FS will instruct Shopify via API to approve the checkout request. If sufficient funds are unavailable, Shopify FS instructs Shopify via API to reject the checkout request.   
     
3. **(A) Shopify FS instructs the Payment Partner to process applicable amount**  
     
   Simultaneously with Step (3)(B) below, Shopify FS instructs the Payment Partner[^4] to process a payment for the applicable Split Payment amount, which was determined during the Shopper’s checkout from the Merchant. The Payment Partner will be responsible for exchanging any payments processed into the Merchant’s preferred payout currency. The Merchant will be responsible to the Payment Partner for any payment processing and/or currency conversion related fees.   
   

**(B) Shopify FS instructs Bank Partner to transfer funds to Payment Partner**

Daily at a minimum, or more frequently, Shopify FS instructs the Bank Partner to send Shop Pay Wallet Balance transaction amounts to the Payment Partner, including the applicable amount for Split Payment transactions. These amounts represent batched Shopper purchases that have been previously approved. Shopify FS payments to Payment Partner may be made in one or many ACH payments, depending on transaction volume. The Bank Partner acts as the ODFI, and the Payment Partner’s bank partner acts as RDFI. In certain circumstances Shopify FS and the Payment Partner may decide to net Shoppers’ payments and refunds against one another. Any amounts flowing between Shopify FS and Payment Partner will be reconciled and agreed to by both parties. 

Shopify FS will provide a unique transaction identifier and total amount owed to the Payment Partner to enable the Payment Partner to ensure that stored value funds and credit card or funds associated with another payment method on a specific transaction are associated with the same payout to the Merchant. 

4. **(A)** **The Payment Partner processes the applicable portion of the Split Payment transaction**

   The Payment Partner processes the portion of the Split Payment transaction that was not made using Shop Pay Wallet Balance. Upon confirmation of successful processing of payment, the Payment Partner receives the funds into the Merchant’s account at the Payment Partner. The Payment Partner will be responsible for exchanging any payments processed into the Merchant’s preferred payout currency. The Merchant will be responsible to the Payment Partner for any payment processing and/or currency conversion related fees. 

   **(B) Bank Partner facilitates the actual movement of funds between Shopify FS (ODFI) and Payment Partner (RDFI)**

   

   Daily at a minimum, or more frequently, Bank Partner acts on Shopify FS’ instructions to send Shop Pay Wallet Balance transaction amounts to the Payment Partner. 

   

5. **The Payment Partner consolidates funds into the merchant’s account**  
     
   The Payment Partner consolidates processed funds from the applicable payment method, the Payment Partner (if applicable), and the funds received from the FBO Account. The Payment Partner deducts applicable fees ahead of consolidating funds into the Merchant’s account. Shopify FS’ money transmission liability for the portion of the Split Payment made using the Shop Pay Wallet Balance is extinguished once funds have been received into the Merchant’s account at the Payment Partner, which is typically within two (2) business days from the day that the transfer is initiated, and a corresponding debit is reflected in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance.  
     
6. **Shopify FS reconciles ledger and bank transaction associated with the purchase**  
     
   Shopify FS compares the decrease in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance with the stored value portion attributed to the Shopper’s purchase to ensure they are equal. This is completed at both the individual transaction and aggregate FBO account levels.  
   

4. **Shopper Seeks a Refund**

**![][image6]**  
**Funds Flow: Refund**

1. **Shopper initiates refund process with a Merchant**  
     
   A Shopper navigates through a Merchant’s transaction refund flow and requests a refund for a past purchase from the Merchant to the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance. Shopify FS is notified of a valid refund to process and instructs the Bank Partner to begin the refund process.   
     
2. **Merchant Accepts the Refund Request**  
     
   Once the Merchant accepts the Shopper’s refund request, the Payment Partner is notified of the accepted refund request via API. The Payment Partner confirms whether the Shopper passes all required compliance checks and is the same Shopper that completed the original transaction. The Payment Partner will then obtain funds from the Merchant and inform Shopify FS of a refund transaction.

 

3. **Refund Process is Initiated**

   For Split Payments, the portion of the purchase made via the Shopper’s Payment Card will be refunded by the Payment Partner to the original payment method, as described in Step (A). For the portion of the purchase made via the Shop Pay Wallet Balance, the Shop Pay Wallet Balance will be credited, as described in Step (B). 

	  
**(A)** **The Payment Partner initiates refund process**

The Payment Partner initiates the refund process and communicates with Payment Card networks to arrange funding for the refund via the original payment method used by the Shopper. The Payment Partner will be responsible for exchanging any payments processed into the original transaction currency. The Merchant will be responsible for any refund processing and/or currency conversion related fees. 

**(B)** **Shopify FS receives refund funds into the FBO Account**

Daily at a minimum, or more frequently, the Payment Partner instructs Shopify FS that they are sending refund transactions to the FBO Account. These amounts represent batched Shopper purchases that have been refunded. The Payment Partner payments to Shopify FS may be in one or many ACH payments, depending on transaction volume. The Payment Partner’s bank partner acts as the ODFI, and the Bank Partner as the RDFI. In certain circumstances Shopify FS and the Payment Partner may decide to net Shoppers’ payments and refunds against one another. Any amounts flowing between Shopify FS and the Payment Partner will be reconciled and agreed to by both parties. 

4. **Shopify FS adjusts availability of funds for Shopper**  
     
   Shopify FS receives the refund funds into the FBO Account and credits the Shop Pay Wallet Balance for the Shopper receiving the refund for the same amount. An equivalent money transmission liability for Shopify FS to the Shopper with respect to the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance is created.  
     
5. **Shopify FS reconciles ledger and bank transaction associated with the purchase**  
     
   Shopify FS compares the increase in the Shopper’s Shop Pay Wallet Balance with the stored value portion attributed to the Shopper’s refund to ensure they are equal.
